## Executive Summary

The European Commission - Humanitarian Aid & Civil Protection is a
top-tier donor with significant total funding of around 4.9 billion USD
and a strong emphasis on earmarked allocations (~25%), surpassing
average donor specificity. Its funding exhibits substantial annual and
regional variability, with allocations peaking near 250 million USD
across diverse regions, notably prioritizing a few high-need countries
such as Ukraine, Lebanon, Turkey, and Uganda. Geographic reach is
rapidly expanding, with the number of recipient countries projected to
grow from 8 to 48 by 2025. Funding transactions are fewer and smaller
than peer donors, characterized by volatility in amounts and timing,
indicating opportunities to advocate for larger, more predictable
commitments aligned to strategic priorities for enhanced program impact.

## Volatility

The funding data for the European Commission’s Humanitarian Aid and
Civil Protection shows an average transaction value of approximately 1.5
million USD, with about 120 transactions recorded annually. In
comparison, the benchmark group of the top 10 other donors exhibits an
average transaction amount nearly twice as large, at 2.9 million USD,
and over three times the transaction frequency, with roughly 378
transactions per year. This lower volume and transaction size indicate a
more conservative and less frequent funding approach by the European
Commission relative to other leading donors. The assessment of
transaction dates spanning from March 2023 to December 2025 reveals
consistent funding activity but with noticeable volatility around
transaction values. The standard deviation of transaction values is
high, reflecting fluctuations in the amounts committed per transaction.
This suggests potential unpredictability in funding windows and amounts,
which can undermine planning and rapid response capacities of
humanitarian partners. From an operational and fundraising perspective,
these patterns emphasize the need for strategies that address funding
reliability and increase transaction frequency or size to align better
with peer donors. Proposal developers should consider advocating for
more predictable and sizable funding commitments from the European
Commission to enhance program continuity and impact. Additionally,
exploring mechanisms to smooth funding volatility could improve the
operational stability of humanitarian programs supported by the
Commission.
